      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>An Oct. 1 letter defends Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's decision to seek the vice presidency and re-election to the Senate simultaneously, on the ground that his doing so reduces the risk of our being deprived of his leadership.</p>
        <p>This amounts to arguing that we cannot afford to have real elections between real candidates, because if we did, then the candidate we like might lose. Some of the world's most despotic regimes use similar logic to save their citizenry the trouble of having to vote at all.</p>
        <p>FRED KAMENY  Chapel Hill, N.C., Oct. 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
